and $M_{R}=3.3\times10^{15}\:\text{GeV}$. The initial VEV of the
$\sigma$ field is $\sigma_{0}=2.7\times10^{16}\:\text{GeV}.$ The
maximum temperature during reheating is $T_{\text{max}}=3.3\times10^{14}\:\text{GeV}$.
The first vertical dashed lines denote the time of maximum reheating,
the first time the $\sigma$ VEV crosses zero, and the beginning of
the radiation-dominated era, form left to right.\label{fig:asymmetry_history}}
\end{figure}


One can obtain the evolution of the lepton asymmetry more precisely
by solving Eq.~\eqref{eq:nL} numerically. In Fig.~\ref{fig:asymmetry_history},
we present a numerical example for $\lambda_{\text{eff}}=10^{-8}$
with the inflationary parameters $\Lambda_{I}=5\times10^{17}\:\text{GeV}$,
and $\Gamma_{I}=3\times10^{6}\:\text{GeV}$. The RH neutrino
mass scale is set at $M_{R}=10T_{\text{max}}$ to suppress the thermal
production of RH neutrinos during reheating, and we verify that the resulting
neutrino Yukawa coupling is within the perturbative regime ($\left|Y_{\nu}\right|^{2}/4\pi=0.88<1$). This example gives a late time asymptotic asymmetry about $\eta\sim10^{-8}$.

As the Universe cools down, we expect the SM degrees of freedom to go out of thermal equilibrium. This decreases the asymmetry by two orders of magnitude due to the entropy production. The electroweak sphalerons then redistribute the excess between leptons and baryons as in thermal leptogenesis. This gives the final baryon asymmetry $\eta\sim10^{-10}$, which agrees with the value currently observed.

\begin{figure}
\begin{centering}
\includegraphics[width=0.6\columnwidth]{Asymmetry_Estimation_2}
\par\end{centering}

\caption{The approximate late time asymptotic asymmetry ($\log\left|\eta\right|$) using Eq.~\eqref{eq:estimation_formula} with $\Gamma_{I}=3 \times 10^{6}\,\text{GeV}$, $M_{R}=10 T_{\text{max}}$, and $M_{n}=0.1T_{\text{max}}$. \label{fig:parameter_space}}
\end{figure}

We explored the parameter space of the model using the approximate
formula (Eq.~\eqref{eq:estimation_formula}). In Fig.~\ref{fig:parameter_space}, we show the approximate late time asymmetry ($\log\left|\eta\right|$) as a function of $\lambda_{\text{eff}}$ and $\Lambda_{I}$ with mass scales $M_{R}=10T_{\text{max}}$ and $M_{n}=0.1 T_{\text{max}}$. The decay rate of the inflaton is set to $\Gamma_{I}=3 \times 10^{6}\:\text{GeV}$ so that it gives the maximum asymmetry for each $\lambda_{\text{eff}}$ and $\Lambda_{I}$. The requirement of the neutrino coupling being perturbative ($\left|Y_{\nu}\right|^{2}/4\pi < 1$) imposes an upper bound on the inflationary energy scale $\Lambda_{I}\lesssim 7 \times 10^{17}\,\text{GeV}$. 


As mentioned before, the region where $\eta\sim10^{-8}$ will give the final asymmetry $\mathcal{O}\left(10^{-10}\right)$ matching the observed value. This is indicated by the dashed line in the figure.  We see that the generated asymmetry increases as $\lambda_{\text{eff}}$ decreases.  This can be understood as follows: the initial VEV is set by inflationary parameters, since by construction, the VEV is permitted only to grow during the last $N \approx 8$ e-folds of inflation.  The relaxation time though scales as $1 \slash \sqrt{ \lambda_{\text{eff}}}$; therefore, as $\lambda_{\text{eff}}$ decreases the system has more time to approach the equilibrium asymmetry.  From this figure, we see the effective quartic coupling is restricted to $\lambda_{\text{eff}}\lesssim 10^{-6}$, which corresponds to a relatively flat effective potential for the $\sigma$ field.  Such flat directions can develop in models with multi-field scalar sectors, such as the EGH model considered here.   

In order to compare with our earlier work using the SM Higgs boson, it is convenient to consider the asymmetry as a function of the new scale $M_n$ and the decay rate of the inflaton, $\Gamma_I$.  This is shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:MnVSGammaI}, where we have fixed the inflationary scale $\Lambda_I$ and coupling $\lambda_\mathrm{eff}$.  In these plots, we additionally illustrate the regime in which $\mathrm{Max}(\sigma_0, T_\mathrm{max}) > M_n$ using cross-hatching.  For these parameters, $M_n$ is not the largest scale in the analysis, and the use of effective field theory to derive Eq.~\eqref{eq:operator} is questionable.  Consequently, the exact asymmetry would depend on the details of the UV-complete theory considered.  Much of the parameter space of interest falls in this regime, as illustrated by the plot on the left.  Nonetheless, if one fine-tunes $\lambda_\mathrm{eff}$ to extremely small values ($\mathcal{O}(10^{-15})$ or smaller), an asymmetry $\eta \sim 10^{-8}$ (prior to the Standard Model degrees of freedom freezing out) can be generated in the regime in which effective field theory is reliable, as illustrated by the plot on the right.

